description.text: A simple printable tool for getting the most out of your tubes of toothpaste, lotion, etc. At a recent trade show, I noticed an astonishing amount of beauty and cosmetic products using the same toothpaste tube-like storing containers. By the end of it, the representatives were struggling to give out samples while the tubes were taking on that all-too-familiar form. ( http://www.re-nest.com/uimages/re-nest/toothpaste.jpg ) I couldn't help but think about how I would solve this problem with a (hypothetical) makerbot. The slot width is made to fit the largest of flattened toothpaste tubes found amongst my friends. The front slot is drafted just a touch to ease the initial insertion of the tube, and the large circular surface is intended to get that last extra bit once the squeezer reaches the back of the nozzle. This design uses a total of 2.7 cubic inches of material.

Considering the abundance of tubes to squeeze, it is recommended that you measure the compressed thickness of the tube you want to squeeze and then scale the .stl file to fit accordingly

description.text:
This is a solid customizable replacement for the standered 2 inch (50mm) office chair wheel with a 8mm pin . The wheels are very solid and my prototypes have stood up to 3 months of abuse with persons up to 250Lb . The wheel support in its current state is standing up very well however i have only 1 week of testing for the wheel support structure.   
I have additional fender designs in the works as well as wheel covers or hubcaps.   
Also another wheel designed for 626ZZ bearings that would allow for a smaller axle M6 Axel bolt for those who may have a hand full of 626ZZ bearings on hand.   
Be the first on your block to have the coolest wheels around.

If you only wish to replace your wheel you will need to remove the axle and drill out the wheel support to accept the M8 Bolt then You will need 2 608Z bearing, 1 M8 60mm bolt, 4 M8 washers, 1 M8 nylock nut (or standard nut with 1 drop of blue Threadlock), 10 M3 16mm Hex socket bolts, 10 M3 Nuts, 10 M3 washers.   
The wheels print well with ABS or PLA I sliced with CURA with 1.2mm Shell Thickness 1.2mm Top/Bottom Thickness. 20% infill.   
The rear bearing cover is part of the structural design of the wheel and must not be left out. It includes Nut traps that will allow a flush mount for the rear of the wheel so it will not interfere with the wheel support. If you wish to use Acorn nuts the nuts traps will allow the Socket bolt head to sit flush in the rear bearing cover.  
Important! When using the Wheel support structure I Have only had time to test it with PLA I sliced with CURA Shell Thickness of 1.5mm and 1.5mm Top and Bottom Thickness. 21% Infill you must use 1.5mm to allow for the internal support structures that i have designed into it to work . Also you must use the wheel support steam to reinforce the top of the wheel support. The fender is optional and only need 3 M3 10mm Hex socket bolts.  
It is very Important not to reorient items to slice them!  I have laid them out in their proper orientation   
This project is still a work in progress and is still in the experimental stage if you print and use this wheel you do so at your own risk I take no responsibility for any damages or injury's that could result from the use of this project.  
If you have any questions or suggestions please leave them in the comments If there are other size stems you may have please let me know and i will make one for that size.  
Happy printing and please share your makes.

(si vous avez des retours ?) Dernier petit point si les trous des ventilos sont décallés, c'est pour laisser de la matière, pour garder en solidité et avoir la place pour les visseries. This catapult has a scientific background. It shows the effect on the range of a projectile, depending on the angle under which the projectile is fired. In this way the catapult can be optimized for the purpose. The base frame has a row of holes in which an M3 bolt can be pushed which will stop the lever. By using one of the other holes, the stopping angle is changed. The catapult is powered by two rubber bands. A trigger button is provided to make firing easier.

It is recommended to print with an infill of 100%. A 100% infill will make the structure stiffer and stronger. The parts fit on a table size  of 20x20 cm. If your table is smaller, it is better to resize the parts than to rotate them. Rotating leads to weaker parts because of the absence of +/- 45 degree layers. The SCAD files are included to make it possible to make changes.

description.text:
This is a servo controlled valve I made for an aquarium water exchanger project based on the one I saw from mikedeklerk. I needed it to be plastic as not to kill my fish. I also left a little ~2 mm gap inbetween the valve boxes to allow for easier fitting. So far it seems the S3003 servo I used has enouph power to turn the valve. I wasn't sure if it work at first without a stronger servo since they seem a bit harder to turn.  
Unfortunally I think they changed the valve design at some point. I had a old one from a scraped project and it was a different design. Hoepfully it would only take some tweeking on the printed part or re-design the valve box and/or valve gear.

Basically print then clean up the parts a bit. I used long M3 screws that I dremeled down to fit without sticking out for the body screws. I used shorter M3's for the servo and M3 nylock nuts for the inset nuts. I also drilled a bigger hole part way for the valve gear screw. I not sure if the newer valve design has a screw or not. I looks like the plastic lever may have to be riped off or cut off. :( Reference the reference to valve below. You should be able to find it a popular hardware stores near you (type 62).. well at least in the US I presume. http://media.wattswater.com/ES-QC-10Valves.pdf

title: Fixture Plates for machining an AR15 80% lower receiver

description.text:
These fixture plates are designed to produce softjaws that allow for holding an 80% AR15 lower receiver to machine the trigger group pocket.   
Also, depending upon how produced it can provide guide bushings to drill out the three holes in the trigger group.  
Was created with AutoDesk Inventor 2014, if you want to modify the files, the original code is provided.  For those of you with other 3D CAD software I am including IGES files of each model, which should be compatible with most software (including FREECAD).

If you decide to 3D print this, the stl files are in inches, so you will need to scale them up by 25.4  
Also the stl files should be rotated so that the y-axis is 'up' on your machine.  Other then that, they do not need support to print.  If using a 3D printed fixture for machining, I suggest that you have thick shells (say 1-1.5mm) and a pretty high density.  I produced with 50% fill, and it seems to work fine.  
You do need two alignment pins to register the two plates with the takedown holes on the AR15

title: Compact extruder with symmetric mount and fan support

description.text: First version of Prusa nozzle used an asymmetrical aluminium mount as cooling plate. Newer version uses a symmetrical one, that means compact extruder part needs a change. This is my version. Rest of the parts may be obtained from https://github.com/josefprusa/Prusa3-vanilla/tree/master/distribution Please note I have upgraded this part to the new x-carriage using 30mm of distance between support holes. Thicker MK7-like drive gears won't fit in the original extruder. I have changed the channel for the drive gear so now it should be possible to use MK7 drive gear (untested). New version added, now with holes for a 40mm fan and a duct. New version just added with bearing capture to avoid it from jumping outside of its place.

Two M3x12 mm and two nuts will be used for fixing the nozzle plate to the block.  
Two 625 bearings and one 608 are needed too.   
M5x66 mm threaded rod will be the main shaft, where a drive gear is attached.  
Two M3x30mm and nuts will fix the idler in place (a 20mm M8 rod is needed for the 608).  
The large gear calls for an M5 lock-nut, a regular nut with a drop of superglue worked for me. The small gear needs you to file a flat on the motor shaft (no fixing screw).  
For fixing a fan, you need the fan version and to tap the two holes with M3x25, you can use two M3x20mm screws then.

title: Adjustable Height Webcam Mount (With Swiveling Option)

description.text:
Height adjustable Webcam mount with g-clamp, printed knobs and caps. Mount designed for the Microsoft Lifecam HD3000.
Update 13/10/2015: Added a new hanging clamp and angled bottom mount to the collection - these are for use on Delta style printers with a square aluminium extrusion type frame. Assembly for this is almost identical to the original desk clamp version. 
Update 04/09/2016: Added a new design called 'SwivelVer' which is much more rugged and allows the mount to swivel.

This webcam stand is designed to clamp onto a desk. The mount is height adjustable and has locking nuts to keep the camera stable. Also included are files for a similar webcam mount for use on Delta style printers with a square aluminium extrusion type frame. Assembly for this is almost identical to the original desk clamp version. Additionally, there is now a version which allows the desk mounted version to swivel 360 degrees. Included is the desk clamp, a mount for a Microsoft Lifecam HD3000, knobs for the clamp and mount bolts, and caps for the clamp bolts to protect your desk surface. A top rod cover is included to protect you against sharp edges on the rods, and also keep the rods parallel. To assemble the mount, print all the parts (I used PLA at 0.2mm layer height, no support and a 25% infill). (If you print the swivel version, support is required due to the recommended orientation for printing to keep the coat hanger wire channels clear). You will need additionally: 1 x metal coat hanger
2 x M4 25mm hex head bolts
2 x M4 12mm hex head bolts
4 x M4 nuts
(if printing the swivel version, you will also need an additional M6 30mm hex head bolt and two M6 nuts)

  • Cut two straight equal lengths from the coat hanger, ensuring that both rods are straight. Length can be decided based on how much vertical movement you need on the camera.

  • Put the knobs onto all four of the bolts - I used SuperGlue and they are nice and solid once it set.

  • Clamp: Insert the nuts into the slots on the clamp - you might find it useful to heat the holes with a hot air gun to avoid splitting the plastic. Once they are in the correct position, screw in the 25mm bolts until you have enough of the bolt showing through to screw the end caps in place. Again, Superglue can be used, but shouldn't be necessary - the bolts should cut a thread into the caps.
    if printing the swivel version, push the M5 bolt through the hole in the shorter centre post, and add the two nuts on top to lock it in place.

  • Using a small amount of SuperGlue, push the rods into the holes on the top of the clamp. Make sure that the tops of the rods are level - the holes go all the way through, so ensure you set them level before the glue sets.
    if printing the swivel version, screw down the top mount plate onto the M5 bolt. Remember you're screwing into plastic, so take it slow and don't force it. You may wish to add a couple of washers to allow easy swiveling without binding.

  • Install the nuts into the camera mount, again using some heat as required.

  • Install the mount onto the rods. Once installed, screw in the 12mm bolts so that they lock against the rod.

  • Finally, install the rod-cover to avoid poking your eye out on the rods!
    • Scaled as is, the clamp will fit onto a desk with a depth of 23mm or less.

author: dfrelow

description.text:
Pylon because it reminded me of Pylons... It was designed to hold Barrel/Crystal dice from Crystal Caste, or at least my set.  
Do note that I included two versions, the pictured version that I added magnets to is scaled to 115%. The original size held a small D20 and the crystal dice except D20.   
The little hole is designed so you can push up a normal D20 or other die so you can remove it without the dice just spinning around. It's ultimately what I settled with, and I recommend you experiment/modify it to find a solution that works for you.  
With the little holes, the barrel D20 does stick out a tad if you don't raise the scale it enough for the D20 to fit inside of the container. I personally prefer using a normal D20 though, as it's easier to read and can rest inside of the container to show the roll.

Printed it at 115% scale to fit my larger D20s. ABS - Hotend 225 C, Bed 89 C
.2 layer height, .3 first layer, 2 Perimeters, 2 bottom shells, 3 top shells. I set Solid Infill threshold area to 5mm^2 in Slic3r 1.2.9 so it wouldn't overdue it on the inner walls. You'll need 2 pieces, as its symmetrical.
After it's printed you'll want a way to keep it together. I used magnets, but one thought was to use notch a couple opposing sides and using a tied ribbon or elastic band to keep it closed. I drilled out holes for magnets and used glue to hold the magnets in. If you want to do that, I recommend you use a higher infill/3D infill to give the glue some anchoring points within the part.
